# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: api-pagination
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:api-pagination/pagination] In reference to books produced without a computer, pagination can mean the consecutive page numbering to indicate the proper order of the pages, which was rarely found in documents pre-dating 1500, and only became common practice c.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] 1550, when it replaced foliation, which numbered only the front sides of folios.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] All of these software tools are capable of flowing the content through algorithms to decide the pagination.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] For example, they all include automated word wrapping (to obviate hard-coded newline delimiters), machine-readable paragraphing (to make paragraph-ending decisions), and automated pagination (to make page-breaking decisions).
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Today printed pages are usually produced by outputting an electronic file to a printing device, such as a desktop printer or a modern printing press.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] These electronic files may for example be Microsoft Word, PDF or QXD files.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] They will usually already incorporate the instructions for pagination, among other formatting instructions.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Pagination encompasses rules and algorithms for deciding where page breaks will fall, which depend partly on cultural considerations about which content belongs on the same page: for example one may try to avoid widows and orphans.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Some systems are more sophisticated than others in this respect.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Before the rise of information technology (IT), pagination was a manual process: all pagination was decided by a human.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Today, most pagination is performed by machines, although humans often override particular decisions (e.g. by inserting a hard page break).
[src:api-pagination/pagination] "Electronic page" is a term to encompass paginated content in presentations or documents that originate or remain as visual electronic documents.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] This is a software file and recording format term in contrast to electronic paper, a hardware display technology.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Electronic pages may be a standard sized based on the document settings of a word processor file, desktop publishing application file, or presentation software file.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Electronic pages may also be dynamic in size or content such as in the case of HTML pages.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] When end-user interactivity is part of the user experience design of an electronic page, it is better known as a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:api-pagination/pagination] The number and size of electronic pages in a document are limited by the amount of computer data storage, not by the display devices or amount of paper.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Most electronic pages are for either display (screen output) on a computer monitor or handheld device, or output to a printing device.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] PDF and some e-book file format pages are designed to do both.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Most applications will print electronic pages without the need for a screen capture.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] However, not all software supports WYSIWYG printing of pages.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Pages exclusively for screen output are more commonly known as screens, windows, interfaces, scenes, or cards.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] In the case of presentation software, electronic pages are known as slides.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Electronic pages displayed on a web browser are often called web pages, regardless of whether they are accessed online via a web server on the World Wide Web, or stored locally offline.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] More accurately, such documents are named by the markup language that makes them displayable via a web browser, e.g.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] With dynamic web pages, pagination is used for such things as displaying a limited number of results on search engine results pages, or showing a limited number of posts when viewing a forum thread.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Pagination is used in some form in almost every web application to divide returned data and display it on multiple pages **within** one web page.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Pagination also includes the logic of preparing and displaying the links to the various pages.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Pagination can be handled client-side or server-side.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] For client-side pagination, the content of each page is included in the HTML source code pre-loaded within the page, while server-side pagination requests each page individually upon navigation.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Client-side pagination can be used when there are very few records to be accessed, in which case all records can be returned, and the client can use JavaScript or CSS to view the separate pages.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] By using AJAX, hybrid server/client-side pagination can be used, in which JavaScript is used to request the subsequent page from the server which is loaded and inserted into the Document Object Model via AJAX.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Server-side pagination is appropriate for large data sets providing faster initial page load, accessibility for those not running Javascript, and complex view business logic, while client-side pagination allows navigating between pages without delay from a server request.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Correctly implementing pagination can be difficult.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] There are many different usability questions such as should "previous" and "next" links be included, how many links to pages should be displayed, and should there be a link to the first and last pages.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Also ability to define the number of records displayed in a single page is useful.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] In comparison to bottomless or infinite scrolling, pagination allows skipping pages and can be implemented with permanent links (as done with the `offset` URL parameter in the MediaWiki wiki engine), whereas infinite scrolling continuously displays material dynamically.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Pagination is an approach used to limit and display only a part of the total data of a query in the database.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Instead of showing hundreds or thousands of rows at the same time, the server is requested only one page (a limited set of rows, per example only 10 rows), and the user starts navigating by requesting the next page, and then the next one, and so on.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] It is very useful, specially in web systems, where there is no dedicated connection between the client and the server, so the client does not have to wait to read and display all the rows of the server.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Today, all content, no matter which output medium is planned, predicted, or not predicted, can be produced with technologies that allow downstream transformations into any presentation desired, although such best-practice preparation is still far from universal.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] This usually involves a markup language (such as XML, HTML, or SGML) that tags the content semantically and machine-readably, which allows downstream technologies (such as XSLT, XSL, or CSS) to output them into whatever presentation is desired.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] This concept is known as the separation of presentation and content.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] This paradigm is now the conventional one in most commercial publishing, except to the extent that legacy and backward compatibility issues and budget constraints interfere, and to the extent that many of the people involved do not understand the topic enough to help build compliance.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] But the need to manually paginate has diminished as the technology for dynamic display and automatic pagination advances.
[src:api-pagination/pagination] Also, there is less need to make a hierarchical distinction between pagination in print and pagination in electronic display, because the same underlying content will most likely be used for the latter exclusively if not for both display methods.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:api-pagination/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:api-pagination/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:api-pagination/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:api-pagination/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
